  <entry>
    <title>Using Lux.jl Experience</title>
    <url>/tomlog/2025/02/28/lux-log/</url>
    <content><![CDATA[<h1 id="Introduction"><a href="#Introduction" class="headerlink" title="Introduction"></a>Introduction</h1><p>Neural networks are very promising for studying actual synaptic behavior in specific human tasks, as they directly mimic neural communications in our brains.</p>
<p>Julia is an excellent choice for implementing neural network simulations due to its flexibility (similar to Python, but with flexible and strict type annotations), JIT compilation for fast computing, and abundant libraries for machine learning.</p>
<p>This article aims to introduce Lux.jl and other libraries primarily as a reference for myself in the future, focusing on the essential steps for creating neural network simulations.</p>
<h1 id="Environment"><a href="#Environment" class="headerlink" title="Environment"></a>Environment</h1><ul>
<li>Ubuntu(WSL) on Windows11</li>
<li>Julia v1.11.3</li>
</ul>
<h1 id="Creating-a-Neural-Network-Model"><a href="#Creating-a-Neural-Network-Model" class="headerlink" title="Creating a Neural Network Model"></a>Creating a Neural Network Model</h1><p>Lux offers several built-in neural network components like Dense, RNN, LSTM, etc., making it easy to create models:</p>
<figure class="highlight julia"><table><tr><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="keyword">using</span> Lux</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">input_dim = <span class="number">8</span></span><br><span class="line">output_dim = <span class="number">4</span></span><br><span class="line">model = Dense(input_dim, output_dim)</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>

<p>To use an activation function, you can define it or use Lux-supported functions (e.g., <code>relu</code> - check the documentation):</p>
<figure class="highlight julia"><table><tr><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">act_fn = x -&gt; tanh.(x)</span><br><span class="line">model = Dense(input_dim, output_dimm activation=act_fn)</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>

<p>You can also chain models with <code>Chain</code>:</p>
<figure class="highlight julia"><table><tr><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="keyword">using</span> Lux</span><br><span class="line">input_dim = <span class="number">2</span></span><br><span class="line">intermediate_dim = <span class="number">16</span></span><br><span class="line">output_dim = <span class="number">1</span></span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line"><span class="comment"># 2 =&gt; 16 =&gt; relu =&gt; 1</span></span><br><span class="line">model = Chain(</span><br><span class="line">    Dense(input_dim, intermediate_dim, relu),</span><br><span class="line">    Dense(intermediate_dim, output_dim),</span><br><span class="line">)</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>

<!-- (TO BE UPDATED) Initializer -->

<h1 id="Initialize-Parameters-and-States"><a href="#Initialize-Parameters-and-States" class="headerlink" title="Initialize Parameters and States"></a>Initialize Parameters and States</h1><p>Unlike Flux.jl, Lux.jl models only define the computation flow - parameters and states are not included in the model definitions. This separation provides more flexibility and control.</p>
<p>You need to generate the parameters and states using <code>Lux.setup</code> before running models. When executing your model, you must provide the <code>input</code>, <code>parameters</code> and <code>states</code>.</p>
<figure class="highlight julia"><table><tr><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="keyword">using</span> Lux, Random</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">input_dim = <span class="number">8</span></span><br><span class="line">output_dim = <span class="number">4</span></span><br><span class="line">model = Dense(input_dim, output_dim) |&gt; f32</span><br><span class="line"><span class="comment"># `|&gt; f32` casts all the numeric values to Float32</span></span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">rng = Random.default_rng() <span class="comment"># you can choose RNG as you like</span></span><br><span class="line">rng = Random.seed!(rng, <span class="number">40</span>) <span class="comment"># fix the rng seed</span></span><br><span class="line">ps, st = Lux.setup(rng, model)</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line"><span class="comment"># try this model!</span></span><br><span class="line">vector_input = [<span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">2</span>, <span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">4</span>, <span class="number">5</span>, <span class="number">6</span>, <span class="number">7</span>, <span class="number">8</span>] |&gt; f32</span><br><span class="line">output, new_st = model(vector_input, ps, st)</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>

<p>The model forward function returns both <code>output</code> and <code>new_state</code>, and the state needs to be updated at a certain appropriate times during training or inference. With the given seed, you might get an output like <code>Float32[5.2590766, 3.3526256, 5.555236, -1.923615]</code>.</p>
<h1 id="Calculate-Gradients"><a href="#Calculate-Gradients" class="headerlink" title="Calculate Gradients"></a>Calculate Gradients</h1><p>If you’ve already learned machine learning basics, you know you need to calculate the gradient of the “loss” from the model output to optimize the model parameters. First, define a loss function that returns a scalar value:</p>
<figure class="highlight julia"><table><tr><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="keyword">function</span> mse_loss(y_true, y_hat)</span><br><span class="line">    <span class="keyword">return</span> sum((y_true - y_hat).^<span class="number">2</span>)</span><br><span class="line"><span class="keyword">end</span></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>

<p>We’ll use <code>Zygote</code>, an automatic differentiation library. For auto-diff, it’s easiest to define a function that takes <code>parameters</code> as its argument and calculates the loss values with your loss function. IMPORTANTLY, <code>y_hat, new_st = model(vector_input, ps, st)</code> must be included within the scope of <code>Zygote.gradient</code>. For some reason, <code>Zygote.gradient</code> occurs some errors in global, so I ran this code in the main function.</p>
<figure class="highlight julia"><table><tr><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="keyword">using</span> Lux, Random, Zygote</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line"><span class="comment"># Zygote may not work properly in global scope</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="keyword">function</span> main()</span><br><span class="line">    input_dim = <span class="number">8</span></span><br><span class="line">    output_dim = <span class="number">8</span></span><br><span class="line">    <span class="comment"># `|&gt; f32` casts all the numeric values to Float32</span></span><br><span class="line">    model = Dense(input_dim, output_dim) |&gt; f32</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">    rng = Random.default_rng() <span class="comment"># you can choose RNG as you like</span></span><br><span class="line">    rng = Random.seed!(rng, <span class="number">40</span>) <span class="comment"># fix the rng seed</span></span><br><span class="line">    ps, st = Lux.setup(rng, model)</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">    <span class="keyword">function</span> mse_loss(y_true, y_hat)</span><br><span class="line">        <span class="keyword">return</span> sum((y_true - y_hat).^<span class="number">2</span>)</span><br><span class="line">    <span class="keyword">end</span></span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">    vector_input = [<span class="number">1</span>, <span class="number">2</span>, <span class="number">3</span>, <span class="number">4</span>, <span class="number">5</span>, <span class="number">6</span>, <span class="number">7</span>, <span class="number">8</span>] |&gt; f32</span><br><span class="line">    y_true = vector_input <span class="comment"># try to learn the identity function (y = x)</span></span><br><span class="line">    grads = Zygote.gradient(</span><br><span class="line">        ps -&gt; <span class="keyword">begin</span></span><br><span class="line">            <span class="comment"># THIS MUST BE INCLUDED IN THE SCOPE!!!</span></span><br><span class="line">            y_hat, new_st = model(vector_input, ps, st)</span><br><span class="line">            st = new_st</span><br><span class="line">            mse_loss(y_true, y_hat)</span><br><span class="line">        <span class="keyword">end</span>,</span><br><span class="line">        ps</span><br><span class="line">    )[<span class="number">1</span>]</span><br><span class="line"><span class="keyword">end</span></span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">main()</span><br><span class="line"></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>

<h1 id="Optimizer"><a href="#Optimizer" class="headerlink" title="Optimizer"></a>Optimizer</h1><p>Now we have obtained gradients of the parameters for the MSE loss. To apply these gradients, we need to prepare an optimizer using <code>Optimisers.jl</code>. Let’s use the Adam optimizer. If you’re familiar with optimization techniques, you might want to clip gradients for more stable learning. You can use <code>ClipGrad</code> or <code>ClipNorm</code> for this purpose, and chain them with the Adam optimizer using <code>Optimisers.OptimiserChain</code>.</p>
<figure class="highlight julia"><table><tr><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="keyword">using</span> Optimisers</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">learning_rate = <span class="number">1e-4</span></span><br><span class="line">opt = Optimisers.OptimiserChain(</span><br><span class="line">    ClipNorm(<span class="number">1.0</span>),</span><br><span class="line">    Adam(learning_rate),</span><br><span class="line">)</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>

<p>Optimizers also need to be initialized with <code>Optimisers.setup(opt, ps)</code>, which returns an “optimizer state” - a set of optimizers for your model parameters. Anyway, just remember you will use <code>opt_state</code> for the optimization process. To apply the optimization, run either <code>Optimisers.update!(opt_state, ps, grads)</code> for in-place updates or <code>opt_state, ps = Optimisers.update(opt_state, ps, grads)</code> for the explicit notation.</p>
<figure class="highlight livecodeserver"><table><tr><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="keyword">using</span> Lux, Random, Zygote, Optimisers</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line"><span class="comment"># Zygote may not work properly in global scope</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="function"><span class="keyword">function</span> <span class="title">main</span>()</span></span><br><span class="line">    input_dim = <span class="number">8</span></span><br><span class="line">    output_dim = <span class="number">8</span></span><br><span class="line">    <span class="comment"># `|&gt; f32` casts all the numeric values to Float32</span></span><br><span class="line">    model = Dense(input_dim, output_dim) |&gt; f32</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">    rng = Random.default_rng() <span class="comment"># you can choose RNG as you like</span></span><br><span class="line">    rng = Random.seed!(rng, <span class="number">40</span>) <span class="comment"># fix the rng seed</span></span><br><span class="line">    ps, st = Lux.setup(rng, model)</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">    learning_rate = <span class="number">1e-4</span></span><br><span class="line">    opt = Optimisers.OptimiserChain(</span><br><span class="line">        ClipNorm(<span class="number">1.0</span>),</span><br><span class="line">        Adam(learning_rate),</span><br><span class="line">    )</span><br><span class="line">    opt_state = Optimisers.setup(opt, ps)</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">    <span class="function"><span class="keyword">function</span> <span class="title">mse_loss</span>(<span class="title">y_true</span>, <span class="title">y_hat</span>)</span></span><br><span class="line">        <span class="literal">return</span> <span class="built_in">sum</span>((y_true - y_hat).^<span class="number">2</span>)</span><br><span class="line">    <span class="function"><span class="keyword">end</span></span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="function"></span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="function">    <span class="title">vector_input</span> = [<span class="title">1</span>, <span class="title">2</span>, <span class="title">3</span>, <span class="title">4</span>, <span class="title">5</span>, <span class="title">6</span>, <span class="title">7</span>, <span class="title">8</span>] |&gt; <span class="title">f32</span></span></span><br><span class="line">    y_true = vector_input <span class="comment"># try to learn the identity function (y = x)</span></span><br><span class="line">    grads = Zygote.gradient(</span><br><span class="line">        ps -&gt; begin</span><br><span class="line">            <span class="comment"># THIS MUST BE INCLUDED IN THE SCOPE!!!</span></span><br><span class="line">            y_hat, new_st = model(vector_input, ps, st)</span><br><span class="line">            st = new_st</span><br><span class="line">            mse_loss(y_true, y_hat)</span><br><span class="line">        <span class="keyword">end</span>,</span><br><span class="line">        ps</span><br><span class="line">    )[<span class="number">1</span>]</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">    display(ps) <span class="comment"># Display parameters before update</span></span><br><span class="line">    opt_state, ps = Optimisers.update(opt_state, ps, grads)</span><br><span class="line">    display(ps) <span class="comment"># Display parameters after update</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="function"><span class="keyword">end</span></span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="function"></span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="function"><span class="title">main</span>()</span></span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line"><span class="comment"># Output before update:</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="comment"># (weight = Float32[-0.33398467 0.43204907 … 0.55984545 0.5002263; -0.029455915 -0.099705815 … 0.3199415 -0.15672576; … ; -0.48615417 0.07889257 … 0.07015245 0.11924155; 0.4749607 -0.31358016 … -0.33515924 0.38729846], bias = Float32[0.22096232, -0.29122669, 0.12903713, -0.3231772, 0.119143665, 0.13592169, -0.23593734, 0.3118714])</span></span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line"><span class="comment"># Output after update:</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="comment"># (weight = Float32[-0.33408466 0.43194908 … 0.55974543 0.5001263; -0.029355915 -0.09960581 … 0.32004148 -0.15662576; … ; -0.48605418 0.078992575 … 0.07025245 0.11934155; 0.4750607 -0.31348017 … -0.33505926 0.38739845], bias = Float32[0.22086231, -0.2911267, 0.12913713, -0.32327718, 0.11924367, 0.13602169, -0.23583734, 0.3119714])RetryClaude does not have the ability to run the code it generates yet.</span></span><br><span class="line"></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>

<h1 id="Training-Flow"><a href="#Training-Flow" class="headerlink" title="Training Flow"></a>Training Flow</h1><p>Now that we’ve covered the basics of running a simple neural network, let’s try to make a feedforward network learn the identity function.</p>
<p>I’ll use two Dense layers: the first extends the input dimension to 8 with a relu activation, and the second outputs a value from the 8-dimensional vector. Since we’re using supervised learning (we have true labels!), I’ll provide random values within the range of <code>xs</code>. For simplicity, I intentionally won’t split the data into test and training sets. To speed up learning, the batch size is set to $min(16, floor(num_sample&#x2F;8))$. <code>Plots.jl</code> allows us to easily create animations, which is extremely useful for visualizing how the learning progresses.</p>
<figure class="highlight julia"><table><tr><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="keyword">using</span> Lux, Random, Zygote, Optimisers, Plots</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line"><span class="keyword">function</span> mse_loss(y_true, y_hat)</span><br><span class="line">    <span class="keyword">return</span> sum((y_true - y_hat).^<span class="number">2</span>)</span><br><span class="line"><span class="keyword">end</span></span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line"><span class="keyword">function</span> main()</span><br><span class="line">    input_dim = <span class="number">1</span></span><br><span class="line">    intermediate_dim = <span class="number">8</span></span><br><span class="line">    output_dim = <span class="number">1</span></span><br><span class="line">    <span class="comment"># `|&gt; f32` casts all the numeric values to Float32</span></span><br><span class="line">    model = Chain(</span><br><span class="line">        Dense(input_dim, intermediate_dim, relu) |&gt; f32,</span><br><span class="line">        Dense(intermediate_dim, output_dim) |&gt; f32,</span><br><span class="line">    )</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">    rng = Random.default_rng() <span class="comment"># you can choose RNG as you like</span></span><br><span class="line">    rng = Random.seed!(rng, <span class="number">40</span>) <span class="comment"># fix the rng seed</span></span><br><span class="line">    ps, st = Lux.setup(rng, model)</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">    learning_rate = <span class="number">1e-3</span></span><br><span class="line">    opt = Optimisers.OptimiserChain(</span><br><span class="line">        ClipNorm(<span class="number">1.0</span>),</span><br><span class="line">        Adam(learning_rate),</span><br><span class="line">    )</span><br><span class="line">    opt_state = Optimisers.setup(opt, ps)</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">    anim = Animation()</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">    xs = collect(<span class="number">0</span>:<span class="number">0.01</span>:<span class="number">2</span>*<span class="literal">pi</span>) |&gt; f32</span><br><span class="line">    num_sample = length(xs)</span><br><span class="line">    batch_size = min(<span class="number">16</span>, num_sample ÷ <span class="number">8</span>)</span><br><span class="line">    episode = <span class="number">0</span></span><br><span class="line">    <span class="keyword">while</span> <span class="literal">true</span></span><br><span class="line">        <span class="comment"># validation</span></span><br><span class="line">        y_hat, _ = model(reshape(xs, <span class="number">1</span>, :, <span class="number">1</span>), ps, st)</span><br><span class="line">        mse_loss(xs, y_hat[:]) &lt; <span class="number">0.5</span> &amp;&amp; <span class="keyword">break</span></span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">        <span class="comment"># plot</span></span><br><span class="line">        plot(xs, xs, label=<span class="string">&quot;ideal&quot;</span>)</span><br><span class="line">        plt = plot!(xs, y_hat[:], label=<span class="string">&quot;model&quot;</span>, title=<span class="string">&quot;episode <span class="variable">$episode</span>&quot;</span>)</span><br><span class="line">        frame(anim, plt)</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">        <span class="comment"># training process</span></span><br><span class="line">        episode = episode + <span class="number">1</span></span><br><span class="line">        x = reshape(rand(rng, xs, batch_size), :, <span class="number">1</span>, batch_size)</span><br><span class="line">        y_hat, st = model(x, ps, st)</span><br><span class="line">        grads, = Zygote.gradient(ps -&gt; <span class="keyword">begin</span></span><br><span class="line">                y_hat, _ = model(x, ps, st)</span><br><span class="line">                mse_loss(x, y_hat)</span><br><span class="line">            <span class="keyword">end</span>,</span><br><span class="line">            ps</span><br><span class="line">        )</span><br><span class="line">        opt_state, ps = Optimisers.update(opt_state, ps, grads)</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">        <span class="comment"># quit condition</span></span><br><span class="line">        episode &gt; <span class="number">5000</span> &amp;&amp; <span class="keyword">break</span></span><br><span class="line">    <span class="keyword">end</span></span><br><span class="line">    <span class="comment"># plot</span></span><br><span class="line">    y_hat, _ = model(reshape(xs, <span class="number">1</span>, :, <span class="number">1</span>), ps, st)</span><br><span class="line">    plot(xs, xs[:], label=<span class="string">&quot;ideal&quot;</span>)</span><br><span class="line">    plt = plot!(xs, y_hat[:], label=<span class="string">&quot;model&quot;</span>, title=<span class="string">&quot;episode <span class="variable">$episode</span>&quot;</span>)</span><br><span class="line">    frame(anim, plt)</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">    <span class="keyword">return</span> anim</span><br><span class="line"><span class="keyword">end</span></span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">anim = main()</span><br><span class="line"></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>

<p>This code generates an animation showing the learning process. While points around x&#x3D;0 aren’t perfectly fitted, the overall result is satisfactory.<br><img src="/tomlog/./lux-log/tmp.gif" alt="learning process animation"><br><img src="/tomlog/./lux-log/tmp.mp4" alt="you might can watch mp4"></p>
<h1 id="Appendix"><a href="#Appendix" class="headerlink" title="Appendix"></a>Appendix</h1><p>Sample codes are available. <img src="/tomlog/./lux-log/main.ipynb" alt="ipynb file"></p>
]]></content>
